  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        (Donnelly 7.32)
      </p>
      <p>
        A social media survey found that <m>69\%</m> of parents <q>follow</q> their children on Instagram.  A random sample of 140 parents was selected.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the standard error of the proportion.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <me>\sigma_p=\sqrt{\frac{0.69(1-0.69)}{140}}\approx 0.0391</me>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the probability that 104 or more parents from this sample <q>follow</q> their children on Instagram?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <me>P\left(\overline{p}\geq \frac{104}{140}\right) = 1-P\left(\overline{p}\lt \frac{104}{140}\right)\approx 0.0869</me>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </task>


    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the probability that between 97 and 104 parents from this sample <q>follow</q> their children on Instagram?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <me>P\left(\frac{97}{140}\lt \overline{p}\lt \frac{104}{140}\right) \approx 0.3812</me>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </task>


    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If 81 parents responded that the <q>follow</q> their children on Instagram, does this result support the findings of the social media survey?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <me>P\left(\overline{p}\leq \frac{81}{140}\right) \approx 0.0023</me>
          Since <m>0.0023\lt 0.05 </m> (less than <m>5\%</m>), the sample with only 81 parents answering <q>yes</q> is unusual.  Therefore, the survey results are questionable.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </task>


  </exercise>

